"Dee Boersma P.","Penguins as marine sentinels",2008,"BioScience","58","7",,"597","607",,,10.1641/B580707,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-48249155482&partnerID=40&md5=d71885c606442707c8b1860201b90a95","Department of Biology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA, United States","Dee Boersma, P., Department of Biology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA, United States","From the tropics to Antarctica, penguins depend on predictable regions of high ocean productivity where their prey aggregate. Increases in precipitation and reductions in sea ice associated with climate warming are affecting penguins. The largest breeding colony of Patagonian (Magellanic) penguins, at Punta Tombo, Argentina, had approximately 200,000 breeding pairs in October 2006 - a decline of 22% since 1987. In the 1980s and 1990s, petroleum pollution was a major source of Patagonian penguin mortality. In 1994, tanker lanes were moved 40 kilometers (km) farther off the coast of Chubut, and the dumping of ballast water and the oiling of penguins are now rare. However, penguins are swimming 60 km farther north from their nests during incubation than they did a decade ago, very likely reflecting shifts in prey in response to climate change and reductions in prey abundance caused by commercial fishing. These temperate penguin species, marine sentinels for southern oceans, demonstrate that new challenges are confronting their populations. © 2008 American Institute of Biological Sciences.","Climate variation; El Niño; Global warming; Marine zoning; Penguins","Spheniscidae",,,,,,"Banks, J., Van Buren, A., Cherel, Y., Whitfield, J.B., Genetic evidence for three species of rockhopper penguins, Eudyptes chrysocome (2006) Polar Biology, 30, pp. 61-67; Barry, J.P., Baxter, C.H., Sagarin, R.D., Gilman, S.E., Climate-related, long-term faunal changes in a California rocky intertidal community (1995) Science, 267, pp. 672-675; Boersma, P.D., An ecological and behavioral study of the Galápagos penguin (1977) Living Bird, 15, pp. 43-93; Boersma, P.D., Galápagos penguins as indicators of oceanographic conditions (1978) Science, 200, pp. 1481-1483; Boersma, P.D., Population trends of the Galápagos penguin: Impacts of El Niño and La Niña (1998) The Condor, 100, pp. 245-253; Boersma, P.D., The 1997-1998 El Niño: Impact on penguins (1998) Penguin Conservation, 11, pp. 10-11; Boersma, P.D., Stokes, D.L., Conservation of penguins: Threats to penguin populations (1995) The Penguins: Spheniscidae, pp. 127-139. , Williams TD, ed, New York: Oxford University Press; Boersma, P.D., Van Buren, A., Penguins (2003) Wildlife Spectacles, pp. 149-152. , Mittermeier RA, Gil PR, Mittermeier CG, Brooks T, Hoffman M, Konstant WR, da Fonseca GAB, Mast R, eds, Mexico City: CEMEX, Agrupación Sierra Madre, Conservation International; Boersma, P.D., Stokes, D.L., Yorio, P., Reproductive variability and historical change of Magellanic penguins (Spheniscus magellanicus) at Punta Tombo, Argentina (1990) Biology of Penguins, pp. 15-43. , Davis L, Darby J, eds, New York: Macmillan; Boersma, P.D., Vargas, F.H., Merlen, G., Living laboratory in peril (2005) Science, 308, p. 925; Boersma, P.D., Rebstock, G.A., Stokes, D.L., Majluf, P., Oceans apart: Conservation models for two temperate penguin species shaped by the marine environment (2007) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 335, pp. 217-225; Boersma, P.D., Frere, E., Rebstock, G.A., Moore, S.E., Following the fish: Penguins and productivity in the South Atlantic (2008) Ecological Monographs, , Forthcoming; Cheney, C., The current situation of the Humboldt penguin in Chile and Peru: A report from the Population and Habitat Viability Analysis meeting (1998) Penguin Conservation, 11, pp. 4-9; Cook, A.J., Fox, A.J., Vaughan, D.G., Ferrigno, J.G., Retreating glacier fronts on the Antarctic Peninsula over the past half-century (2005) Science, 308, pp. 541-544; Crawford, R.J., Underhille, L.G., Upfold, L., Dyer, B.M., An altered carrying capacity